						               													<description>&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#136;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#170;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#131;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#175;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#175;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#168;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#185;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#136; (Trick Quest) is a trick-taking role-playing game from Japan. Players have RPG roles such as mage or fighter, and progress along an adventure path by winning tricks. When a player wins cards in suit matching their character, they can improve their abilities.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each player gets a RPG character and work together to complete the quest. Players move along a path on a game board, and where the path diverges, they can split or stay together. Players can work up and down the path, repeating sections to build up their characters.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;As players face each challenge, they play a trick-taking game. The suits correspond to the characters; armour for the martial artist, tools for the mage and wizard, ornaments for the monk and so on. By collecting cards in their suit, a character can get Trick Points (TP) and use them to upgrade their abilities, and to level up to unlock higher strengths.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players win the game by completing the quest, finding the legendary GodBird and ridding the world of disease.&amp;#10;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
